= Final Words

This book started as notes to myself. Things I was learning, mistakes I was making, patterns I was noticing. I wrote them down because I needed to make sense of what was happening — to my craft, to my workflow, to the way I think about building software.

Somewhere along the way, the notes became chapters, and the chapters became this book.

== What I Believe

I believe the craft of software engineering is not dying. It's shedding its skin. The part that was always mechanical — the typing, the boilerplate, the repetitive plumbing — that's being absorbed by machines. What remains is the part that was always human: the judgement, the taste, the ability to look at a system and know what it _should_ be.

I believe agents are not replacements for engineers. They are amplifiers. A mediocre engineer with agents produces mediocre software faster. A great engineer with agents produces great software at a pace that was previously impossible. The differentiator was never typing speed. It was always thinking.

I believe the engineers who thrive in this new world will be the ones who invest in the fundamentals — context management, guardrails, testing, conventions, clear communication — rather than chasing the latest tool. Tools change every six months. Principles endure.

== What I Got Wrong

I'm sure parts of this book are already wrong. The landscape moves fast. A technique I swear by today might be obsolete by the time you read this. A tool I recommended might have been replaced by something better.

That's fine. The specific tools were never the point. The point is the _thinking_ — how to reason about autonomy, how to structure work for agents, how to maintain your own judgement while leveraging theirs. If I've helped you develop that thinking, the book did its job, even if every code example is outdated.

== The Crew Metaphor, One Last Time

You're the captain. The agents are your crew. The ship is whatever you're building — a product, a system, a company, a career.

A good captain doesn't do everything alone. That's not strength — it's a bottleneck. A good captain also doesn't hand over the wheel and go below deck. That's not delegation — it's abdication.

The art is in the middle. You set the course. You make the calls that matter. You trust your crew with the work they're good at, and you stay close enough to intervene when the sea gets rough. You build trust over time, task by task, commit by commit.

Some days the crew will surprise you with how good they are. Other days they'll do something baffling and you'll wonder why you bothered. Both are normal. The relationship gets better with practice, like any working relationship does.

== Go Build Something

The best way to learn agentic engineering is to do it. Not to read about it — though I hope this book gave you a useful foundation — but to open a terminal, point an agent at a real problem, and watch what happens.

Start small. Fix a bug. Write some tests. Refactor a module. Pay attention to what works and what doesn't. Adjust your workflow. Try again.

Then go bigger. Run two agents in parallel. Set up worktree isolation. Build a pipeline. Break something, learn from it, build a guardrail.

The engineers who will define this era aren't waiting for permission or certainty. They're experimenting, shipping, and learning — with a crew at their side.

I hope you'll be one of them.

